Young female second left.
See also: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/249179738; https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/249180473; and https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/249181110.

Adult male top right.
See also: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/249179738; https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/249180664; and https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/249181110.

Not the Nile Crocodile.
You males except for adult male right above and young female second from left.
Not sure what killed the crocodile. According to other visitors, the young lions killed the crocodile, and others, to learn the art of killing and to eliminate competition around the empty waterholes because of the drought - not confirmed though. See also: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/249178434 for another crocodile nearby apparently killed by the lions. 
See also: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/249180473; https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/249180664; and https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/249181110.

Not the birds.
Carcass being fed on by White-backed Vultures, Lappet-faced Vulture and Maraboe Storks.
Question: Why do one see vultures having a free lunch with predators such as lions an hyena's around?
See also: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/249157156; https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/249158030; and https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/249158516.
